You are right, this general functionality cannot be implemented with better asymptotic time complexity. 

However `uniq_by(array, iteratee=None)` uses the same implementation, but knowing that the comparator is out of the equation this can be implemented more efficiently somehow like this
```python
def uniq_by(array, iteratee=lambda x: x):
    seen_hashable = set()
    seen_unhashable = []
    for item in array:
        item_key = iteratee(item)
        if isinstance(item_key, collections.Hashable):
            if item_key not in seen_hashable:
                yield item
                seen_hashable.add(item_key)
        else:
            if item_key not in seen_unhashable:
                yield item
                seen_unhashable.append(item_key)
```

This issue get to me by some colleagues that used `uniq_by` as a blackbox alghorithm and we were surprised by the low speed. Actually some details about the performance in the docstring couldn't help us either, as they didn't read it, so it's only us to blame. :)
Anyway, if somebody needs a better method they can build it with ease specifically for their use case.

Thanks for the quick response anyway.

