In that case I see one issue: returning `None` would cause `Image()` to fail, because it expects a Numpy-array. This could be tackled in `Format.Reader.get_data()` or in `Image.__new__()`, but I guess it would be preferable not to mess around with those, and limit any edit to the ffmpeg plugin?

Perhaps, instead of returning `None`, we could add an item to the return-dict (image metadata) from `FfmpegFormat.Reader._get_data()`? This way the `mode` parameter would not be necessary (unless we also want to add a blocking mode). This seems like the most minimally-invasive solution to me. For example:

