Thank you for your answer.

I just found a workaround in order to use declaration symbols present in my SMT file.

Let's say I have this SMT file (`foo.smt2`) generated from an external tool:
```
(set-logic QF_ABV)
(set-info :smt-lib-version 2.0)
(declare-fun a () (_ BitVec 32))
(declare-fun c () (_ BitVec 32))
(define-fun b () (_ BitVec 32) (bvadd c (_ bv4 32)))
```

Now from my C++ code with the Z3 API I would like to ask `a != b?`. So I do:
```cpp
context c;
solver s(c);
expr foo = c.parse_file("foo.smt2");
s.add(foo);
expr a = c.bv_const("a", 32);
expr b = c.bv_const("b", 32);
s.add(a != b);
check_result r = s.check();
```

But, if I understand, it doesn't work because the `foo` expr is empty because there is no assertion in `foo.smt2`. That's right?

So my workaround is to add "fake" assertion in my SMT file like that:
```
(set-logic QF_ABV)
(set-info :smt-lib-version 2.0)
(declare-fun a () (_ BitVec 32))
(declare-fun c () (_ BitVec 32))
(define-fun b () (_ BitVec 32) (bvadd c (_ bv4 32)))

(declare-fun a_end () (_ BitVec 32))
(assert (= a a_end))

(declare-fun b_end () (_ BitVec 32))
(assert (= b b_end))
```

Now if I do:

```cpp
context c;
solver s(c);
expr foo = c.parse_file("foo.smt2");
s.add(foo);
expr a = c.bv_const("a_end", 32);
expr b = c.bv_const("b_end", 32);
s.add(a != b);
check_result r = s.check();
```

It works!

But I'm not sure if my workaround is good? Maybe there is a better solution? 

What do you think about that?

Thank you for your help!

