We should not be messing with Python's inheritance behavior any more than necessary. `class Meta` can be inherited just like a normal class.

```python
from marshmallow import Schema

class Parent(Schema):
    class Meta:
        ordered = True


class Child(Schema):
    class Meta(Parent.Meta):
        pass

assert Child().opts.ordered is True
```

Another (IMHO more pyramidic) way to deal with this is to use a single *acl* for the service and different *permissions* for different methods.

E.g. (mostly ripped from the [pyramid docs](http://docs.pylonsproject.org/projects/pyramid/en/latest/narr/security.html#assigning-acls-to-your-resource-objects), and completely untested): 
```
from cornice import Service
from pyramid.security import Allow, Everyone, DENY_ALL

class RootFactory(object):
    def __init__(self, request):
        pass

    __acl__ = [
        (Allow, Everyone, 'view'),
        (Allow, 'group:editors', 'edit'),
        DENY_ALL,
        ] 

user_info = Service(name='users', path='/{username}/info', factory=RootFactory)

@user_info.get(permission='view')
def get_info(request):
    ....

@user_info.post(permission='edit')
def set_info(request):
    ....

